What is Hypothesis Testing

Researchers retain or reject hypothesis based on measurements of observed samples

To determine whether retain or reject is based on “Hypothesis Testing”

How to state the hypotheses

  • Null hypothesis: an assumption that is made about the larger population, denoted by \(H_0\)
  • Alternative hypothesis: negates the null hypothesis, denoted by \(H_1\)

For example

  • Null hypothesis: there would be an equal number of occurrences of heads and tails if a coin is tossed several times(a fair coin!)
  • Alternative hypothesis: the occurrences of heads and tails would have significant differences if a coin is tossed several times(an unfair coin!)

A common metric called p-value is applied to decide whethter to accept or reject null hypothesis

  • A small p-value (typically ≤ 0.05) indicates strong evidence against the null hypothesis, so you reject it
  • A large p-value (> 0.05) indicates weak evidence against the null hypothesis, so you accept it

Types of error

There are 2 types of error might occur after we decided to accept or reject null hypothesis

  1. Type I error: falsely rejecting a TRUE \(H_0\)
  2. Type II error: falsely accepting a FALSE \(H_0\)

Understanding these 2 errors via confusion matrix

In confusion matrix

  • Positive refers to rejecting hypothesis
  • Negative refers to accepting hypothesis

There are 4 possible combinations

  1. TP: truly rejecting a FALSE \(H_0\)
  2. TN: truly accepting a TRUE \(H_0\)
  3. FP: falsely rejecting a TRUE \(H_0\)
  4. FN: falsely accepting a FALSE \(H_0\)

If confusion matrix makes you too confused…

The probability of committing decision errors

  • The probability of committing a Type I Error is denoted by \(\alpha\)
  • The probability of committing a Type II Error is denoted by \(\beta\)

Updating row indice

row.names(titanic) <- NULL

The Built-In var() and sd() Functions uses denominator of n-1

?var
?sd

Creating our own functions for population variance and standard deviation

population_variance <- function(x) {
  n <- length(x)
  mu <- mean(x)
  error <- x - mu
  squared_error <- error**2
  sum_squared_error <- sum(squared_error)
  return(sum_squared_error / n)
}

population_sd <- function(x) {
  pop_var <- population_variance(x)
  return(sqrt(pop_var))
}

Lower Tail Test of Population Mean with Known Variance

Null hypothesis of the lower tail test of the population mean

\[\mu \ge \mu_0\]

The test statistic \(z\)

\[z = \frac{\bar{x} - \mu_0}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\]

The null hypothesis of the lower tail test is to be rejected if \(z \le -z_{\alpha}\)

Problem

Suppose the historian claims that the mean age of Titanic passengers is older than 40 years old. In a sample of 30 passengers, it was found that they are 31.28 years old on average. At .05 significance level, can we reject the claim by the historian?

set.seed(87)
row_indice <- as.numeric(rownames(titanic))
sampled_row_indice <- sample(row_indice, size = 30)
sampled_titanic <- titanic[sampled_row_indice, ]
mean(sampled_titanic$Age)
## [1] 31.28333

Solution

x_bar <- mean(sampled_titanic$Age)
mu_0 <- 40
sigma <- population_sd(titanic$Age)
n <- 30
z <- (x_bar - mu_0)/(sigma/sqrt(n))
z
## [1] -3.288929
alpha <- .05
z_alpha <- qnorm(1 - alpha)
-z_alpha
## [1] -1.644854

Interpretation

The test statistic -3.288929 is less than the critical value of -1.644854. Hence, at .05 significance level, we reject the claim that mean age of Titanic passengers is older than 40 years old.

Upper Tail Test of Population Mean with Known Variance

Null hypothesis of the lower tail test of the population mean

\[\mu \le \mu_0\]

The test statistic \(z\)

\[z = \frac{\bar{x} - \mu_0}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\]

The null hypothesis of the lower tail test is to be rejected if \(z \ge z_{\alpha}\)

Problem

Suppose the historian claims that the mean age of Titanic passengers is younger than 20 years old. In a sample of 30 passengers, it was found that they are 31.28 years old on average. At .05 significance level, can we reject the claim by the historian?

Solution

x_bar <- mean(sampled_titanic$Age)
mu_0 <- 20
sigma <- population_sd(titanic$Age)
n <- 30
z <- (x_bar - mu_0)/(sigma/sqrt(n))
z
## [1] 4.257371
alpha <- .05
z_alpha <- qnorm(1 - alpha)
z_alpha
## [1] 1.644854

Interpretation

The test statistic 4.257371 is greater than the critical value of 1.644854. Hence, at .05 significance level, we reject the claim that mean age of Titanic passengers is younger than 20 years old.

Two-Tailed Test of Population Mean with Known Variance

Null hypothesis of the two-tailed test of the population mean

\[\mu = \mu_0\]

The test statistic \(z\)

\[z = \frac{\bar{x} - \mu_0}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\]

The null hypothesis of the lower tail test is to be rejected if \(z \le -z_{\alpha/2}\) or \(z \ge z_{\alpha/2}\)

Problem

Suppose the historian claims that the mean age of Titanic passengers in a sample of 30 passengers is the same as population, it was found that they are 31.28 years old on average. At .05 significance level, can we reject the claim by the historian?

Solution

x_bar <- mean(sampled_titanic$Age)
mu_0 <- mean(titanic$Age)
sigma <- population_sd(titanic$Age)
n <- 30
z <- (x_bar - mu_0)/(sigma/sqrt(n))
z
## [1] 0.5977483
alpha <- .05
z_half_alpha <- qnorm(1 - alpha/2)
c(-z_half_alpha, z_half_alpha)
## [1] -1.959964  1.959964

Interpretation

The test statistic 0.5977483 which lies between the critical values of -1.959964 and 1.959964. Hence, at .05 significance level, we do not reject the claim that the sample mean age of Titanic passengers is the same as population.

Lower Tail Test of Population Mean with Unknown Variance

Null hypothesis of the lower tail test of the population mean

\[\mu \ge \mu_0\]

The test statistic \(t\)

\[t = \frac{\bar{x} - \mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}\]

The null hypothesis of the lower tail test is to be rejected if \(t \le -t_{\alpha}\)

Problem

Suppose the historian claims that the mean age of Titanic passengers is older than 40 years old. In a sample of 30 passengers, it was found that they are 31.28 years old on average. At .05 significance level, can we reject the claim by the historian?

Solution

x_bar <- mean(sampled_titanic$Age)
mu_0 <- 40
s <- population_sd(sampled_titanic$Age)
n <- 30
t <- (x_bar - mu_0)/(s/sqrt(n))
t
## [1] -4.745267
alpha <- .05
t_alpha <- qt(1 - alpha, df = n - 1)
-t_alpha
## [1] -1.699127

Interpretation

The test statistic -4.745267 is less than the critical value of -1.699127. Hence, at .05 significance level, we reject the claim that mean age of Titanic passengers is older than 40 years old.

Two-Tailed Test of Population Mean with Unknown Variance

Null hypothesis of the two-tailed test of the population mean

\[\mu = \mu_0\]

The test statistic \(t\)

\[t = \frac{\bar{x} - \mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}\]

The null hypothesis of the two-tailed test is to be rejected if \(t \le -t_{\alpha/2}\) or \(t \ge t_{\alpha/2}\)

Problem

Suppose the historian claims that the mean age of Titanic passengers in a sample of 30 passengers is the same as population, it was found that they are 31.28 years old on average. At .05 significance level, can we reject the claim by the historian?

Solution

x_bar <- mean(sampled_titanic$Age)
mu_0 <- mean(titanic$Age)
s <- population_sd(sampled_titanic$Age)
n <- 30
t <- (x_bar - mu_0)/(s/sqrt(n))
t
## [1] 0.8624313
alpha <- .05
t_half_alpha <- qt(1 - alpha/2, df = n - 1)
c(-t_half_alpha, t_half_alpha)
## [1] -2.04523  2.04523

Interpretation

The test statistic 0.8624313 which lies between the critical values of -2.04523 and 2.04523. Hence, at .05 significance level, we do not reject the claim that the sample mean age of Titanic passengers is the same as population.
